      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 49-year-old man with congestive heart failure, elevated liver enzymes, and greyish skin pigmentation is diagnosed with CCF, hepatitis, and liver cirrhosis. A liver biopsy reveals marked iron accumulation. Based on this patient&rsquo;s presentation, what is the molecular nature of iron (Fe) in the body?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1910884",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30586,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C) Stored in combination with ferritin</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Ferrous iron Fe2+ </strong>is the absorption form in the <strong>intestine </strong>by <strong>ferritin </strong>&rarr; <strong>transported </strong>by <strong>transferrin </strong>in plasma &rarr; <strong>stored </strong>in the <strong>liver </strong>in combination with <strong>ferritin </strong>or as <strong>hemosiderin</strong>. Hence <strong>option A&nbsp;&amp; D</strong>&nbsp;are ruled out.&nbsp; </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Also <strong>excessive iron </strong>uptake over many years &rarr; <strong>hemochromatosis </strong>&rarr; extensive <strong>hemosiderin </strong>deposition in the <strong>liver</strong>, <strong>myocardium, pancreas, and adrenals </strong>&rarr; C/F: <strong>cirrhosis, CCF, diabetes mellitus and skin pigmentation</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A. Stored in the spleen and absorbed in the intestine by albumin:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Iron </strong>is indeed <strong>stored </strong>in the <strong>spleen</strong>, but it is <strong>not </strong>absorbed in the <strong>intestine </strong>by <strong>albumin</strong>. <strong>Iron absorption </strong>occurs in the <strong>duodenum </strong>and is mediated by the <strong>protein transferrin</strong>, not albumin.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. Excreted in the urine as Fe 2+:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Iron </strong>is <strong>not </strong>typically excreted in <strong>urine </strong>in significant amounts. The <strong>body tightly </strong>regulates <strong>iron </strong>excretion since there is <strong>no active excretory pathway </strong>for <strong>iron</strong>; instead, <strong>iron is lost </strong>through <strong>shedding of intestinal cells, skin cells, and blood loss.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. Absorbed in the ferric (Fe 3+) form:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Iron </strong>is <strong>absorbed </strong>in the <strong>intestine primarily </strong>in the <strong>ferrous (Fe 2+) form. </strong>It is <strong>reduced </strong>from its <strong>ferric (Fe 3+) form </strong>to the <strong>ferrous </strong>form by <strong>duodenal cytochrome B </strong>or <strong>vitamin C </strong>before <strong>absorption</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Iron </strong>in the body is <strong>stored </strong>in combination with <strong>ferritin</strong>, a protein that <strong>binds </strong>and sequesters <strong>iron in a safe </strong>form <strong>within cells, </strong>preventing <strong>iron-mediated oxidative damage</strong>. The <strong>patient&#39;s symptoms and biopsy</strong> findings suggest <strong>iron overload,</strong> which could be consistent with <strong>hereditary hemochromatosis</strong> or <strong>secondary hemochromatosis</strong> due to <strong>chronic transfusions</strong> or <strong>other causes.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Harper 30/e: p 541,550.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
