      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 68432,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Iron levels decrease, but he remains anaemic.</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 68433,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Iron levels decrease, and anaemia recovers.</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 68434,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">He develops irreversible and severe agranulocytosis.</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 68435,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Iron and vitamin C levels decrease.</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A physician treats a 10-year-old boy who is not agranulocytic with subcutaneous infusions of deferoxamine, an iron chelator, and monitors his progress over several weeks. Assuming the treatment is effective and well-tolerated, what outcome might be expected upon re-examination after a few weeks of therapy?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1945581",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30587,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. A) Iron levels decrease, but he remains anemic.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The<strong> iron chelator </strong>helps in excreting <strong>iron </strong>but has <strong>no </strong>role in <strong>increasing </strong>red blood cell (<strong>RBC</strong>) production to <strong>counteract anaemia</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. Iron levels decrease, and anemia recovers:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This outcome would be expected if the <strong>anemia </strong>were <strong>directly </strong>due to <strong>iron overload</strong>, and <strong>reducing iron levels </strong>effectively addresses the <strong>cause of anemia</strong>. However, if the <strong>anemia </strong>is due to <strong>other reasons</strong>, such as <strong>nutritional deficiencies or bone marrow disorders</strong>, merely <strong>decreasing iron </strong>levels with <strong>deferoxamine </strong>might <strong>not </strong>lead to recovery from <strong>anemia.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C. He develops irreversible and severe agranulocytosis:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Agranulocytosis, a severe <strong>decrease </strong>in <strong>neutrophil count</strong>, is <strong>not </strong>a typical side effect of <strong>deferoxamine treatment</strong>. This option suggests an outcome <strong>unrelated </strong>to the known <strong>pharmacological effects </strong>of <strong>deferoxamine </strong>and is <strong>not </strong>an expected consequence of <strong>its use </strong>in treating <strong>iron overload</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. Iron and vitamin C levels decrease:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> While <strong>deferoxamine </strong>is designed to <strong>chelate and reduce iron levels</strong>, it does <strong>not </strong>inherently affect <strong>vitamin C levels</strong>. <strong>Vitamin C&nbsp;</strong>role in <strong>enhancing iron absorption </strong>is well-documented, but its levels <strong>wouldn&#39;t </strong>be directly <strong>decreased </strong>by <strong>deferoxamine </strong>treatment. Any change in <strong>vitamin C levels </strong>would <strong>more </strong>likely result from <strong>dietary factors </strong>or <strong>other treatments </strong>rather than deferoxamine use.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Deferoxamine </strong>can effectively <strong>reduce excess iron levels </strong>in cases of <strong>iron overload</strong>, it <strong>does not </strong>directly address the production of <strong>red blood cells </strong>or other <strong>underlying causes of anemia</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Vasudevan 9/e: 517-519.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
