        {
          "id": 68496,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Iron </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 68497,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Sodium </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 68498,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Potassium </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 68499,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Chromium</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Which of the following elements is sometimes described as a &quot;one way substance&quot; due to its physiological behavior, particularly in absorption and minimal excretion?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6500895",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30584,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans.&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A) Iron</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A:</span></strong> </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Iron </strong>is unique among <strong>trace elements</strong> due to its<strong> limited pathways</strong> for <strong>excretion.</strong> The human body has a <strong>sophisticated system</strong> for <strong>recycling iron,</strong> particularly from <strong>old red blood cells</strong>, and <strong>its homeostasis</strong> is primarily regulated at the level of <strong>absorption </strong>from the <strong>gastrointestinal tract</strong>. Because there are <strong>no active mechanisms for iron excretion,</strong> the body controls <strong>iron levels </strong>mainly through the regulation of<strong> its absorption</strong>, making it somewhat akin to a &quot;<strong>one-way substance.&quot;</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. Sodium -</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Sodium is readily <strong>excreted </strong>and <strong>regulated </strong>by the<strong> kidneys, </strong>and its physiological behavior does<strong> not </strong>match the description of a <strong>&quot;one-way substance&quot;</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C. Potassium -</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Similar to sodium, <strong>potassium</strong> is also <strong>well-regulated </strong>by the<strong> kidneys, </strong>and the body can adjust <strong>its excretion </strong>based on <strong>dietary intake</strong> and <strong>physiological needs.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. Chromium -</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Chromium is an <strong>essential trace element</strong> involved in the metabolism of <strong>carbohydrates, fat, and protein</strong>. While important, its<strong> absorption and excretion </strong>patterns<strong> do not</strong> typically warrant the description of a <strong>&quot;one-way substance&quot;</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Mucosal Block Theory</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Sites </strong>of absorption: <strong>Duodenum and jejunum.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In <strong>Iron metabolism,</strong> the <strong>homeostasis</strong> is maintained by regulation at the <strong>level of absorption</strong> and not by excretion. Thus, iron is a one-way element.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">When <strong>iron stores </strong>in the body are<strong> depleted,</strong> <strong>absorption</strong> is enhanced and if an <strong>adequate quantity of iron</strong> is <strong>stored, </strong>the absorption is<strong> decreased.</strong> This is known as the &ldquo;<strong>mucosal block</strong>&rdquo; of regulation of <strong>absorption of iron.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Vasudevan 9/e: 515.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
