      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B) False</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Absorption </strong>of <strong>iron </strong>needs a <strong>divalent metal ion transporter </strong>and <strong>ferroportin. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Synthesis </strong>of these <strong>two proteins</strong> is <strong>down regulated by hepcidin</strong>, a peptide secreted by the <strong>liver </strong>if the body <strong>iron reserves </strong>are<strong> adequate</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">During<strong> hypoxia or anaemia</strong>, the <strong>synthesis of hepcidin </strong>is <strong>reduced</strong>, thus <strong>ferroportin synthesis </strong>will <strong>increase</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Hepcidin <strong>decreases surface expression</strong> of the <strong>ferroportin</strong>, which is responsible for moving <strong>iron across cell membranes. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Hepcidin</strong> production is<strong> increased</strong> by <strong>high iron stores and during inflammation</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Hepcidin </strong>actually downregulates <strong>ferroportin </strong>by <strong>binding </strong>to it, leading to its <strong>internalization and degradation</strong>. <strong>Ferroportin </strong>is a <strong>cellular iron </strong>exporter found on the <strong>surface of cells </strong>that store or transport iron, such as <strong>enterocytes in the gut</strong>, <strong>hepatocytes in the liver</strong>, and <strong>macrophages</strong>. <strong>Hepcidin</strong>, a <strong>liver-synthesized hormone</strong>, plays a key role in <strong>iron homeostasis </strong>by <strong>inhibiting iron </strong>export through its action on <strong>ferroportin</strong>, thereby <strong>reducing dietary iron absorption </strong>and <strong>iron release </strong>from <strong>macrophages and hepatocytes.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Vasudevan 9/e: p 516.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
