      "map_id": 30582,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. A) Cirrhosis, Hemochromatosis and Diabetes</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">When total body <strong>iron</strong> is<strong> higher</strong><strong> </strong>than<strong> 25&ndash;30 g,</strong> it is known as<strong> hemosiderosis. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In the<strong> liver</strong>, <strong>hemosiderin </strong>deposit leads to <strong>death of cells and cirrhosis.</strong> </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Pancreatic&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">cell <strong>death</strong> leads to<strong> diabetes.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Deposits under the <strong>skin</strong> cause yellow-brown discoloration, known as <strong>hemochromatosis</strong><em>. </em></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>triad of cirrhosis, hemochromatosis and diabetes</strong> are referred to as <strong>bronze diabetes.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/11/screenshot-2024-04-11-101657.png\" style=\"height:370px; width:600px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. Cirrhosis and diabetes:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> While <strong>both </strong>conditions may be present in &quot;<strong>bronze diabetes</strong>,&quot; the term specifically includes <strong>hemochromatosis</strong> as well. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C. Hemochromatosis and diabetes:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This pair is <strong>part of the bronze diabetes </strong>triad but on its own <strong>does not </strong>constitute the <strong>complete syndrome. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. Cirrhosis, hemochromatosis, and not diabetes:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Diabetes</strong> is a key component of &quot;<strong>bronze diabetes,&quot; </strong>and thus, this option is i<strong>ncorrect.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>&quot;Bronze diabetes</strong>&quot; is the classic triad of<strong> diabetes mellitus, skin pigmentation, and cirrhosis</strong> associated with primary <strong>hemochromatosis</strong>. This syndrome underscores the importance of considering underlying <strong>systemic causes,</strong> such as<strong> iron overload</strong>, in patients presenting with<strong> diabetes </strong>and<strong> unexplained skin pigmentation.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Vasudevan 9/e: p520.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
