      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B) 20 mg of iron + 100 mg folic acid</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Oral iron</strong> supplementation is the <strong>treatment of choice. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>100 mg</strong> of <strong>iron </strong>+<strong> 500 mg</strong> of <strong>folic acid </strong>are given to <strong>pregnant women</strong> and <strong>20 mg </strong>of <strong>iron</strong> + <strong>100 mg folic acid </strong>to <strong>children. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Iron tablets</strong> are usually given along with <strong>vitamin C, </strong>to convert it into <strong>ferrous form,</strong> for easy<strong> absorption. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Unabsorbed iron</strong> may generate <strong>free radicals. </strong>So, it is advisable to give <strong>vitamin E </strong>(to prevent free radical generation) along with iron.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective</span></u></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The treatment of <strong>iron deficiency anemia</strong> in children typically includes<strong> oral iron supplementation.</strong> The recommended dosage of <strong>elemental iron </strong>for children is <strong>3-6 mg/kg/day</strong>, which usually amounts to about <strong>20 mg per day</strong> for a child of this age. Although <strong>folic</strong> <strong>acid supplementation</strong> is <strong>not </strong>always necessary for<strong> iron deficiency anemia</strong>, it can be <strong>beneficial</strong> in some cases, especially if the patient is at <strong>risk of folate deficiency</strong> as well</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Vasudevan 9/e: 519.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
